summary:
The Security Council,

Welcomes the Secretary-General's report on UNFICYP, noting developments over the last six months;

Notes the Government of Cyprus's agreement to keep UNFICYP beyond 15 December 2007 due to prevailing conditions;

Echoes the Secretary-General's view that finding a solution lies with the Cypriots, and the upcoming year offers a window of opportunity for progress;

Takes note of the generally stable security situation, decrease in incidents, and urges both sides to avoid actions increasing tension;

Underlines that buffer zone activities, particularly large-scale commercial projects, should not compromise stability and security;

Welcomes the 8 July 2006 Agreement principles, stressing a bicommunal, bizonal federation and political equality as key to a comprehensive settlement;

Deplores the failure to implement the 8 July 2006 Agreement, urging leaders to start the process without delay;

Welcomes agreements on demining activities, progress on missing persons, and proposed confidence-building measures;

Encourages bicommunal contacts, events, and civil society engagement;

Reaffirms the importance of the Secretary-General's review of UNFICYP's operations and mandate;

Welcomes steps taken by the Republic of Cyprus to address living conditions of UNFICYP troops;

Echoes the Secretary-General's gratitude for voluntary contributions to UNFICYP and requests further contributions;

Welcomes efforts to sensitize peacekeeping personnel on HIV/AIDS and communicable diseases;

1. Welcomes the analysis on developments on the ground over the last six months in the Secretary-General's report.
The Security Council:

2. Reaffirms the status quo on Cyprus is unacceptable and negotiations to reunify the island have stalled; 

3. Supports the 8 July process, notes lack of progress, and urges parties to engage constructively with UN efforts to make measurable progress; 

4. Reaffirms relevant resolutions on Cyprus, particularly resolution 1251 (1999);

5. Supports UNFICYP and extends its mandate until 15 June 2008;

6. Urges both sides to consult with UNFICYP on buffer zone demarcation and the 1989 aide-memoire;

7. Calls on Turkish Cypriot side and forces to restore military status quo in Strovilia;

8. Requests a report on resolution implementation by 1 June 2008;

9. Welcomes UNFICYP's efforts to prevent sexual exploitation and abuse, and urges troop-contributing countries to take preventive action;

10. Remains seized of the matter.
